page.text: The proposed project involves the rezoning of a portion of the Lawrence Aviation
Industries site for purposes of developing an industrial park, with a variety of permitted
uses. The ± 103.73 acres are located on the south side of the Long Island Railroad
(LIRR) Port Jefferson Branch / Village of Port Jefferson boundary, north of the proposed
NYS Route 25A bypass “State Route 5232A” Right of Way (currently a shared-use
pedestrian / bicycle Greenway Trail) within the Hamlet of Port Jefferson Station. The
site is bordered on the west and east by residential and industrial uses. This site is the
largest and single most important undeveloped site throughout the hamlet, comprising
35% of all privately-owned vacant land and 46% of all vacant non-residential land in the
hamlet. The site is currently zoned as a mixture of B-1 (Residential) and L-1 (Light
Industry) uses. T he site location is illustrated on Figures A and 1 as shown on t he

performed. In addition, the effects of the additional traffic on the surrounding roadway

2. The capacity of a signalized intersection is calculated in terms of the ratio of the
demand flow rate to capacity (V/C ratio). Capacity is specified for each approach of
an intersection, and measures the maximum hourly flow of vehicles (for each
individual approach) that can be discharged through the intersection under the
prevailing roadway, traffic, and signalization conditions.
Level of Service (LOS) for signalized intersections is defined in terms of delay.
Delay is a measure of driver discomfort, frustration, fuel consumption, and loss of
travel time. Specifically, level of service criteria are stated in terms of the average
stopped delay per vehicle for a 60 m inute analysis period. T he criteria and travel
condition of the respective LOS are as follows:

3. The capacity of an unsignalized intersection is measured in terms of the gap

opportunities to safely navigate their way through the intersection. T he second
component is the manner in which the distribution of gaps of a particular size in the
traffic stream on the major approach is made available to the motorist when
Level of Service (LOS) for unsignalized intersections is defined by the computed or
measured control delay for each minor movement. LOS is not defined for the
intersection as a whole. T he control delay includes the initial deceleration delay,
queue start-up time, stopped delay, and final acceleration. The average control delay
is a function of the approach as well as the degree of saturation. The criteria and
travel condition of the respective LOS are as follows:

1. The proposed project involves the development of an industrial park with a variety of
permitted mixed uses, which is situated on ± 103.73 acres. Providing incentives for
site solar energy production / generation is also being considered for this proposed
site. T he construction of a solar farm would have minimal, almost negligible trip
generation, and therefore is not being included in the proposed build out since only a
few employees would be needed to manage and run a solar farm of 50+ acres.
2. Included in the investigation for this study was the preparation of an estimate of the
amount of traffic generated by the development for the proposed project. Th is
estimate was developed utilizing the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) Trip
. F or purposes of this analysis, the rates
contained under Land Use Code 130 (Industrial Park), was utilized in order to
estimate the number of trips generated by the proposed site. T he trip generation
computations and summary appear in the Table on the following page. As shown in
the table, it is anticipated that the proposed project will generate 627 total trip-ends

ends during the PM peak period (127 entering and 476 exiting trips).

The intersections at Sheep Pasture Road & Old Town Road, Sheep Pasture Road & Hulse
